# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carrack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The carrack, which was reputedly one of the richest ever to set sail from the Indies, was lost in an explosion which denied the English, as well as the Portuguese and Spanish, the treasure.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] By virtue of the Iberian Union, the Anglo-Portuguese Treaty of 1373 was in abeyance, and as the Anglo–Spanish War was still ongoing, Portuguese shipping was a fair target for the English navy and privateers.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] At the latter end of 1593, the Earl of Cumberland, hoping to capitalize on the success of the previous year's capture of the *Madre de Deus*, prepared at his own expense three ships of 250 to 300 tons, with two artillery decks each and a total of 420 sailors and soldiers.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] These ships included the *Royal Exchange*, owned by London Merchants William Holliday, Thomas Cordell and William Garraway, and of which George Cave was captain; the *Mayflower*, Vice Admiral under the command of William Anthony; and the *Sampson*, under Nicholas Downton.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] There was also a support pinnace, the *Violet*.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] On 6 April 1594 Cumberland's fleet set sail from Plymouth, heading for the Azores.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] En route they roamed the coast of Portugal and Spain, capturing a number of ships.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Off Viana do Castelo, Portugal, a 28-ton barque was captured as it headed towards Portuguese Angola.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Near the islands of Berlengas another three Portuguese and Spanish caravels were taken, one of which had twelve butts of Spanish wine and another a small chest of silver.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] These were sent back to England under prize crews aboard the *Violet* while the rest of the fleet continued towards the Azores.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] They were hoping to avoid Alonso de Bazán's Spanish fleet, which was on the lookout for Cumberland after his failure to intercept him two years earlier.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] On 22 June 1594, as they approached Faial Island, the *Mayflower* saw a great sail approach them and realized it belonged to a huge Portuguese carrack.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The fleet leaving Goa had also included *Santo Alberto* and *Nossa Senhora da Nazareth*; both sprang fatal leaks earlier in the voyage and were beached on the coast of Mozambique.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] *Cinco Chagas* took aboard such cargo in diamonds and other precious gems as had been salvaged from the two lost ships, as well as their 400 passengers and crew members, of which 230 were slaves.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Among them were also two VIPs: Nuno Velho Pereira, the former colonial governor of Mozambique, and Dom Braz Correia, the captain of the fleet that had been returning from the Indies.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The *Chagas* called in at Luanda, in Portuguese Angola, for supplies, where they took aboard more slaves which constituted more mouths to feed.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] By the time the *Chagas* reached the Azores, disease had claimed almost half the complement, many of whom were women and children, and much of the food had been thrown overboard in order to lighten the ship during gales off South Africa.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The carrack attempted to reach the island of Corvo in order to replenish these lost provisions, but contrary winds prevented this, and so she tacked towards Faial.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Soon afterwards, however, the lookouts on *Chagas* spotted the English ships, and prepared for battle.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] At noon all four ships began exchanging broadsides and musket volleys in a battle that lasted for nearly a whole day.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The English ships tried to board the *Cinco Chagas* but were repelled by the larger Portuguese numbers.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] As casualties mounted on both sides the decks of the carrack were cluttered with the dead and wounded.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The battle went on with the English trying to board the ship three times.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] All three attempts were repelled by the Portuguese, putting up a brave fight knowing the riches were too great to lose.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] George Cave, captain of the *Mayflower*, was killed, which discouraged his men from attacking.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The crew of *Sampson* was repulsed with losses and fighting continued for several hours with the four ships moored to each other.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Shortly after, the other two ships, having lost hope of mastering *Chagas*, drifted off and Nicholas Downton was severely wounded and William Antony later was mortally wounded.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The English, having noticed that *Cinco Chagas* had no guns aft, returned to the attack in a deft manoeuvre and concentrated their fire on the stern panel of the carrack.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The *Royal Exchange* made another boarding attempt, this time succeeding in carrying the ship after bitter fighting.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Whilst the heavy hand-to-hand fighting was ongoing, a fire started on a tarpaulin and then spread further to the rigging and the masts.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The fire could not be put out because sharpshooters on board the English ships were taking the Portuguese one by one as they tried to man the pumps.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Seeing the fire spreading out of control and with the English gaining the upper hand, the Portuguese decided to abandon ship, grabbing anything that could float.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] At the same time the English came among them in some armed boats, and began shooting or lancing the helpless Portuguese in the water.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] It became apparent that the only people being spared this butchery were women who were stripping off their outer clothing, "in the hope of piety from the English".
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] However, one lady, Dona Isabel Pereira, whose late husband Diogo de Melo Coutinho had been Captain-major and Tanadar-mor of Ceylon, and her 16-year-old daughter Dona Luisa de Melo Coutinho, steadfastly refused to undress for the privateers and, tying themselves together with a sash of St.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Francis (i.e., the cord which a Franciscan friar would tie around his waist), they went to the opposite side of the ship from the English and leapt into the sea.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] They were buried on Faial where their dead bodies washed ashore, still bound together, the next day.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] When the fire became completely out of control the English decided to lay off from the *Chagas* and "worked furiously to disengage their ships".
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The carrack burned all through the night until just after dawn, when the flames reached the powder magazine in her lower hold, containing "her poulder which was lowest being 60 barrels" which then ignited and "blew her abroad, so that most of the ship did swim in parts above the water".
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The explosion was enormous, killing hundreds of Portuguese including men, women and children, as well as nearly 35 English sailors who were still aboard when the ship exploded.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Most were killed outright and the battle ended with the total loss of the *Chagas* and its cargo.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The crew grabbed any floating remains that were of any use, which proved to be little, and the English began picking up survivors, of which there were only thirteen out of 600 Portuguese.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The English fleet subsequently sailed further west in the hope of rich pickings, and encountered another carrack, the *San Fellipe*, two weeks later.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] With heavy losses already due to disease, and with officers wounded or killed, supplies running low, and a gale forcing them apart, Cumberland decided against engaging the carrack and sailed home.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The cargo of *Cinco Chagas* (along with the salvaged cargo from the two other ships) was worth well in excess of 2,000,000 ducats, and in addition there were twenty-two treasure chests of diamonds, rubies, and pearls estimated to be worth US$15–20 billion by 2017 values.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The prisoners that were saved told their captors that yielding had been impossible as the riches were for the king of Spain and Portugal and that the captain, being highly in the king's favor, would upon his return have been made viceroy in the Indies.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] With the destruction of the *Chagas*, Cumberland had to satisfy himself that the Portuguese and Spanish were denied any of the riches on board.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] He successfully evaded attempts by the Spanish navy to find him.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Alonso de Bazán failed to intercept Cumberland partly because he was hoping to protect the West Indian treasure fleet which was still in the Caribbean.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Another fleet under Don Antonio De Urquiola also failed to find the English, despite his having been in the same area when they headed home past Cape St.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The fleet arrived in Portsmouth on 28 August, and the ships were thoroughly searched when they arrived by the Queen's troops, a consequence of the mass theft from the *Madre de Deus* two years earlier.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Dom Nuno Velho Pereira and Dom Braz Correia had survived the explosion of the *Chagas* and were brought ashore as prisoners, where the Earl treated them well and entertained them for a whole year as his guests.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] They were then ransomed for 2,500 ducats each; Pereira paid for both, making Cumberland's 1594 expedition gain at least some reward.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] With this money the Earl then decided to finance and build a new, larger ship, rather than borrowing from the Queen; the new ship was launched in 1595 and was named by the Queen the *Scourge of Malice*.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] According to the Venetian ambassador to Spain, the *Cinco Chagas* was the richest ship ever to sail from the East Indies.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] Estimates of the location of the wreck of the *Cinco Chagas* suggest that it lies in seas over one mile deep in the Atlantic Ocean, eighteen miles south of the channel between Pico Island and Faial, along with its precious cargo of diamonds and other gems.
[src:carrack/action-of-faial] The wreck has been searched for by treasure hunters but no signs have been found, partly because of the depth.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque advanced the three-fold Portuguese grand scheme of combating Islam, spreading Christianity, and securing the trade of spices by establishing a Portuguese Asian empire.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Among his achievements, Albuquerque managed to conquer Goa and was the first European of the Renaissance to raid the Persian Gulf, and he led the first voyage by a European fleet into the Red Sea.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was appointed head of the "fleet of the Arabian and Persian sea" in 1506.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Many of the conflicts in which he was directly involved took place in the Indian Ocean, in the Persian Gulf regions for control of the trade routes, and on the coasts of India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His military brilliance in these initial campaigns enabled Portugal to become the first global empire in history.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He led the Portuguese forces in numerous battles, including the conquest of Goa in 1510 and the capture of Malacca in 1511.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] During the last five years of his life, he turned to administration, where his actions as the second governor of Portuguese India were crucial to the longevity of the Portuguese Empire.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He oversaw expeditions that resulted in establishing diplomatic contacts with the Ayutthaya Kingdom through his envoy Duarte Fernandes, with Pegu in Myanmar, and Timor and the Moluccas through a voyage headed by António de Abreu and Francisco Serrão.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He laid the path for European trade with Ming China through Rafael Perestrello.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He also aided in establishing diplomatic relations with Ethiopia, and established diplomatic ties with Persia during the Safavid dynasty.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Throughout his career, he received epithets such as "the Terrible", "the Great", "the Lion of the Seas", "the Portuguese Mars", and "the Caesar of the East".
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso de Albuquerque was born in 1453 in Alhandra, near Lisbon.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was the second son of Gonçalo de Albuquerque, Lord of Vila Verde dos Francos, and Dona Leonor de Menezes.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His father held an important position at court and was connected by remote illegitimate descent with the Portuguese monarchy.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was a descendant of King Denis's illegitimate son, Afonso Sanches, Lord of Albuquerque.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was educated in mathematics and Latin at the court of Afonso V of Portugal, where he befriended Prince John, the future King John II of Portugal.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1471, under the command of Afonso V, he was present at the conquest of Tangier and Arzila in Morocco, and he served there as an officer for some years.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1476, he accompanied Prince John in wars against Castile, including the Battle of Toro.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He participated in the campaign on the Italian peninsula in 1480 to assist Ferdinand I of Naples in repelling the Ottoman invasion of Otranto.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On his return in 1481, when John was crowned as King John II, Albuquerque was made master of the horse and chief equerry (**estribeiro-mor**) to the king, a post which he held throughout John's reign.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1489, he returned to military campaigning in North Africa, as commander of defense in the Graciosa fortress, an island in the river Luco near the city of Larache.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1490 Albuquerque was part of the guard of John II.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He returned to Arzila in 1495, where his younger brother Martim died fighting by his side.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] When King Manuel I of Portugal ascended to the throne following the death of his cousin John II, he held a cautious attitude towards Albuquerque, who was a close friend of his predecessor and seventeen years Manuel's senior.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Eight years later, on 6 April 1503 Albuquerque was sent on his first expedition to India together with his cousin Francisco de Albuquerque.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Each commanded three ships, sailing with Duarte Pacheco Pereira and Nicolau Coelho.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] They engaged in several battles against the forces of the Zamorin of Calicut (*Calecute*, Kozhikode) and succeeded in establishing the king of Cochin (*Cochim*, Kochi) securely on his throne.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In return, the king of Cochin gave the Portuguese permission to build the Portuguese fort *Immanuel* (Fort Kochi) and establish trade relations with Quilon (*Coulão*, Kollam).
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] This laid the foundation for the eastern Portuguese Empire.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque returned home in July 1504 and was well received by King Manuel I.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After he assisted with the creation of a strategy for the Portuguese efforts in the east, King Manuel entrusted him with the command of a squadron of five vessels in the fleet of sixteen sailing for India in early 1506, headed by Tristão da Cunha.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The aim of the expedition was to conquer Socotra and build a fortress there, hoping to close the trade in the Red Sea.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque went as "chief-captain for the Coast of Arabia", sailing under da Cunha's orders until reaching Mozambique.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He carried a sealed letter with a secret mission ordered by the king: after fulfilling the first mission, he was to replace the first viceroy of India, Francisco de Almeida, whose term ended two years later.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Before departing, he legitimized his son Brás ("Braz" in the old Portuguese spelling), born to a common Portuguese woman named Joana Vicente in 1500.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque piloted his ship himself, having lost his appointed pilot on departure.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In Mozambique Channel, they rescued Captain João da Nova, who had encountered difficulties on his return from India; da Nova and his ship, the *Flor de la mar*, joined da Cunha's fleet.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] From Malindi, da Cunha sent envoys to Ethiopia, which at the time was thought to be closer to India than it actually is, under the aegis of Albuquerque.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After failing to reach Ethiopia, he managed to land the envoys in Filuk.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After successful attacks on Arab cities on the East African coast, the expedition conquered the island of Socotra and built a fortress at Suq, hoping to establish a base to stop the Red Sea commerce to the Indian Ocean.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] However, Socotra was abandoned four years later, as it was eventually realised to be a poor location for a base.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At Socotra, they parted ways: Tristão da Cunha sailed for India, where he would relieve the Portuguese besieged at Cannanore, while Afonso took seven ships and 500 men to Ormuz in the Persian Gulf, one of the chief eastern centers of commerce.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On his way, he conquered the cities of Curiati (Kuryat), Muscat in July 1507, and Khor Fakkan, accepting the submission of the cities of Kalhat and Sohar.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He arrived at Hormuz on 25 September and soon captured the city, which agreed to become a tributary state of the Portuguese king.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Ormuz was then a tributary state of Shah Ismail I (r.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In a famous episode, shortly after its conquest, Albuquerque was confronted by Persian envoys, who demanded the payment of the due tribute from him instead.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He ordered them to be given a stock of cannonballs, arrows and weapons, retorting that "such was the currency struck in Portugal to pay the tribute demanded from the dominions of King Manuel".
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] According to Brás de Albuquerque, it was Shah Ismael who first addressed Albuquerque as "Lion of the seas".
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso began building the Fort of Our Lady of Victory (later renamed Fort of Our Lady of the Conception) on Hormuz Island, engaging his men of all ranks in the work.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] However, some of his officers, claiming that Afonso was exceeding his orders, revolted against the heavy work and climate and departed for India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] With his fleet reduced to two ships and left without supplies, he was unable to maintain his position.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In January 1508, he was forced to abandon Ormuz.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He raided coastal villages to resupply the settlement of Socotra, returned to Ormuz, and then headed to India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso arrived at Cannanore on the Malabar coast in December 1508, where he opened the sealed letter that he had received from the king before the viceroy, Dom Francisco de Almeida, which named him as governor to succeed Almeida.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The viceroy, supported by the officers who had abandoned Afonso at Ormuz, had a matching royal order but declined to yield.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He protested that his term ended only in January and stated his intention to avenge his son's death by fighting the Mamluk fleet of Mirocem, refusing Afonso's offer to fight the Mamluk fleet himself.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso avoided confrontation, which could have led to civil war, and moved to Kochi, India, to await further instruction from the king.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Increasingly isolated, he wrote to Diogo Lopes de Sequeira, who arrived in India with a new fleet, but was ignored as Sequeira joined Almeida.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At the same time, Afonso refused approaches from opponents of Almeida who encouraged him to seize power.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 3 February 1509, Almeida fought the naval Battle of Diu against a joint fleet of Mamluks, Ottomans, the Zamorin of Calicut, and the Sultan of Gujarat.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His victory was decisive: the Ottomans and Mamluks abandoned the Indian Ocean, easing the way for Portuguese rule there for the next century.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In August, after a petition from Afonso's former officers with the support of Diogo Lopes de Sequeira claiming him unfit for governance, Afonso was sent in custody to St.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] There he remained under what he considered as imprisonment.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso was released after three months' confinement, on the arrival at Cannanore of the Marshal of Portugal Fernando Coutinho with a large fleet sent by the king.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Coutinho was the most important Portuguese noble to visit India up to that point.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He brought an armada of fifteen ships and 3,000 men to defend Afonso's rights, and to take Calicut.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 4 November 1509, Afonso became the second Governor of Portuguese India, a position he would hold until his death.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Almeida set off to return to Portugal, but he was killed before he got there in a skirmish with the Khoekhoe.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Upon his assuming office, Afonso intended to dominate the Muslim world and control the spice trade.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Initially, King Manuel I and his council in Lisbon tried to distribute the power by outlining three areas of jurisdiction in the Indian Ocean.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1509, the nobleman Diogo Lopes de Sequeira was sent with a fleet to Southeast Asia, to seek an agreement with Sultan Mahmud Shah of Malacca, but failed and returned to Portugal.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] To Jorge de Aguiar was given the region between the Cape of Good Hope and Gujarat.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was succeeded by Duarte de Lemos, but left for Cochin and then for Portugal, leaving his fleet to Afonso.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In January 1510, obeying the orders from the king and aware of the absence of the Zamorin, Afonso advanced on Calicut.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The attack was initially successful, but unravelled when Marshal Coutinho, infuriated by Albuquerque's success against Calicut and desiring glory for himself, attacked the Zamorin's palace against Albuquerque's advice, and was ambushed.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] During the retreat, Afonso was badly wounded and was forced to flee to the ships, barely escaping with his life, while Coutinho was killed.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Soon after the failed attack, Afonso assembled a fleet of 23 ships and 1200 men.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Contemporary reports state that he wanted to fight the Egyptian Mamluk Sultanate fleet in the Red Sea or return to Hormuz.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] However, he had been informed by Timoji (a privateer in the service of the Hindu Vijayanagara Empire) that it would be easier to fight them in Goa, where they had sheltered after the Battle of Diu, and also of the illness of the Sultan Yusuf Adil Shah, and war between the Deccan sultanates.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] So he relied on surprise in the capture of Goa from the Sultanate of Bijapur.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] A first assault took place in Goa from 4 March to 20 May 1510.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His fleet was scattered, and a palace revolt in Kochi hindered his recovery, so he headed to Fort Anjediva.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] New ships arrived from Portugal, which were intended for the nobleman Diogo Mendes de Vasconcelos at Malacca, who had been given a rival command of the region.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Three months later, on 25 November Afonso reappeared at Goa with a renovated fleet.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Diogo Mendes de Vasconcelos was compelled to accompany him with the reinforcements for Malacca and about 300 Malabari reinforcements from Cannanore.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In less than a day, they took Goa from Ismail Adil Shah and his Ottoman allies, who surrendered on 10 December.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] It is estimated that 6000 of the 9000 Muslim defenders of the city died, either in the fierce battle in the streets or by drowning while trying to escape.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso regained the support of the Hindu population, although he frustrated the initial expectations of Timoji, who aspired to become governor.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso rewarded him by appointing him chief "Aguazil" of the city, an administrator and representative of the Hindu and Muslim people, as a knowledgeable interpreter of the local customs.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He then made an agreement to lower the yearly tribute.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In Goa, Afonso established the first Portuguese mint in the East, after Timoja's merchants had complained of the scarcity of currency, taking it as an opportunity to solidify the territorial conquest.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The new coin, based on the existing local coins, showed a cross on the obverse and an armillary sphere (or "esfera"), King Manuel's badge, on the reverse.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Gold cruzados or *manueis*, silver *esferas* and *alf-esferas*, and bronze "leais" were issued.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque founded at Goa the *Hospital Real de Goa* or Royal Hospital of Goa, by the Church of Santa Catarina.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Upon hearing that the doctors were extorting the sickly with excessive fees, Albuquerque summoned them, declaring that "You charge a physician's pay and don't know what disease the men who serve our lord the King suffer from.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Thus, I want to teach you what is it that they die from" and put them to work building the city walls all day till nightfall before releasing them.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite constant attacks, Goa became the center of Portuguese India, with the conquest triggering the compliance of neighbouring kingdoms: the Sultan of Gujarat and the Zamorin of Calicut sent embassies, offering alliances and local grants to fortify.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso then used Goa to secure the spice trade in favor of Portugal and sell Persian horses to Vijayanagara and Hindu princes in return for their assistance.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The King of Portugal has often commanded me to go to the Straits, because...this was the best place to intercept the trade which the Moslems...carry on in these parts.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] So it was to do Our Lord's service that we were brought here; by taking Malacca, we would close the Straits so that never again would the Moslems be able to bring their spices by this route....
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] I am very sure that, if this Malacca trade is taken out of their hands, Cairo and Mecca will be completely lost.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In February 1511, through a friendly Hindu merchant, Nina Chatu, Afonso received a letter from Rui de Araújo, one of the nineteen Portuguese held at Malacca since 1509.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] It urged moving forward with the largest possible fleet to demand their release, and gave details of the fortifications.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso showed it to Diogo Mendes de Vasconcelos, as an argument to advance as a joint fleet.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In April 1511, after fortifying Goa, he gathered a force of about 900 Portuguese, 200 Hindu mercenaries and about eighteen ships.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He then sailed to Malacca against orders and despite the protest of Diogo Mendes, who claimed command of the expedition.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso eventually centralized the Portuguese government in the Indian Ocean.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After the Malaccan conquest, he wrote a letter to the king to explain his disagreement with Diogo Mendes, suggesting that further divisions could be harmful to the Portuguese in India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Under his command was Ferdinand Magellan, who had participated in the failed embassy of Diogo Lopes de Sequeira in 1509.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After a false start towards the Red Sea, they sailed to the Strait of Malacca.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] It was the richest city that the Portuguese tried to take, and a focal point in the trade network where Malay traders met Gujarati, Chinese, Japanese, Javanese, Bengali, Persian and Arabic, among others, described by Tomé Pires as of invaluable richness.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite its wealth, it was mostly a wooden-built city, with few masonry buildings but was defended by a mercenary force estimated at 20,000 men and more than 2000 pieces of artillery.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Its greatest weakness was the unpopularity of the government of Sultan Mahmud Shah, who favoured Muslims, arousing dissatisfaction amongst other merchants.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso made a bold approach to the city, his ships decorated with banners, firing cannon volleys.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He declared himself lord of all the navigation, demanded the Sultan release the prisoners and pay for damages, and demanded consent to build a fortified trading post.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The Sultan eventually freed the prisoners, but was unimpressed by the small Portuguese contingent.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso then burned some ships at the port and four coastal buildings as a demonstration.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The city being divided by the Malacca River, the connecting bridge was a strategic point, so at dawn on 25 July, the Portuguese landed and fought a tough battle, facing poisoned arrows, taking the bridge in the evening.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After fruitlessly waiting for the Sultan's reaction, they returned to the ships and prepared a junk (offered by Chinese merchants), filling it with men, artillery and sandbags.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Commanded by António de Abreu, it sailed upriver at high tide to the bridge.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After a fierce fight during which the Sultan appeared with an army of war elephants, the defenders were dispersed and the Sultan fled.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso waited for the reaction of the Sultan.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Merchants approached, asking for Portuguese protection.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] They were given banners to mark their premises, a sign that they would not be looted.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 15 August, the Portuguese attacked again, but the Sultan had fled the city.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Under strict orders, they looted the city, but respected the banners.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso prepared Malacca's defenses against a Malay counterattack, building a fortress, assigning his men to shifts and using stones from the mosque and the cemetery.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite the delays caused by heat and malaria, it was completed in November 1511, its surviving door now known as "A Famosa" ('the famous').
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] It was possibly then that Afonso had a large stone engraved with the names of the participants in the conquest.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] To quell disagreements over the order of the names, he had it set facing the wall, with the single inscription *Lapidem quem reprobaverunt aedificantes* (Latin for "The stone the builders rejected", from David's prophecy, Psalm 118:22–23) on the front.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He settled the Portuguese administration, reappointing Rui de Araújo as factor, a post assigned before his 1509 arrest, and appointing rich merchant Nina Chatu to replace the previous Bendahara.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Besides assisting in the governance of the city and the first Portuguese coinage, he provided the junks for several diplomatic missions.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Meanwhile, Afonso arrested and had executed the powerful Javanese merchant Utimuti Raja who, after being appointed to a position in the Portuguese administration as representative of the Javanese population, had maintained contacts with the exiled royal family.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 20 November 1511 Afonso sailed from Malacca to the coast of Malabar on the old *Flor de la Mar* carrack that had served to support the conquest of Malacca.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Despite its unsound condition, he used it to transport the treasure amassed in the conquest, given its large capacity.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He wanted to give the court of King Manuel a show of Malaccan treasures.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] There were also offerings from the Ayutthaya Kingdom (Thailand) to the king of Portugal, and all his own fortune.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On the voyage, the *Flor de la Mar* was wrecked in a storm, and Afonso barely escaped drowning.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Most Muslim and Gujarati merchants having fled the city, Afonso invested in diplomatic efforts demonstrating generosity to Southeast Asian merchants, like the Chinese, to encourage good relations with the Portuguese.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Knowing of Siamese ambitions over Malacca, Afonso sent Duarte Fernandes in a diplomatic mission to the Ayutthaya Kingdom (Thailand), returning in a Chinese junk.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was one of the Portuguese who had been arrested in Malacca, having gathered knowledge about the culture of the region.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] There he was the first European to arrive, establishing amicable relations between the kingdom of Portugal and the court of the king of Siam Ramathibodi II, returning with a Siamese envoy bearing gifts and letters to Afonso and the king of Portugal.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In November, after having secured Malacca and learning the location of the then secret "spice islands", Afonso sent three ships to find them, led by trusted António de Abreu with deputy commander Francisco Serrão.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Malay sailors were recruited to guide them through Java, the Lesser Sunda Islands and the Ambon Island to Banda Islands, where they arrived in early 1512.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] There they remained for a month, buying and filling their ships with nutmeg and cloves.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] António de Abreu then sailed to Amboina whilst Serrão sailed towards the Moluccas, but he was shipwrecked near Seram.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Sultan Abu Lais of Ternate heard of their stranding, and, seeing a chance to ally himself with a powerful foreign nation, brought them to Ternate in 1512 where they were permitted to build a fort on the island, the *Forte de São João Baptista de Ternate*, built in 1522.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso returned from Malacca to Cochin, but could not sail to Goa as it faced a serious revolt headed by the forces of Ismael Adil Shah, the Sultan of Bijapur, commanded by Rasul Khan and his countrymen.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] During Afonso's absence from Malacca, the Portuguese who opposed the taking of Goa had waived its possession, even writing to the king that it would be best to let it go.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Held up by the monsoon and with few forces available, Afonso had to wait for the arrival of reinforcement fleets headed by his nephew D.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Garcia de Noronha, and Jorge de Mello Pereira.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] While at Cochin, Albuquerque started a school.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In a private letter to King Manuel I, he stated that he had found a chest full of books with which to teach the children of married Portuguese settlers (*casados*) and Christian converts, of which there were about a hundred, to read and write.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 10 September 1512, Afonso sailed from Cochin to Goa with fourteen ships carrying 1,700 soldiers.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Determined to recapture the fortress, he ordered trenches dug and a wall breached.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] But on the day of the planned final assault, Rasul Khan surrendered.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso demanded the fort be handed over with its artillery, ammunition and horses, and the deserters to be given up.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Some had joined Rasul Khan when the Portuguese were forced to flee Goa in May 1510, others during the recent siege.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Rasul Khan consented, on condition that their lives be spared.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He did spare the lives of the deserters, but had them horribly mutilated.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] One such renegade was Fernão Lopes, bound for Portugal in custody, who escaped at the island of Saint Helena and led a 'Robinson Crusoe' life for many years.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After such measures the town became the most prosperous Portuguese settlement in India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In December 1512 an envoy from Ethiopia arrived at Goa.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Mateus was sent by the regent queen Eleni, following the arrival of the Portuguese from Socotra in 1507, as an ambassador for the king of Portugal in search of a coalition to help face growing Muslim influence.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was received in Goa with great honour by Afonso, as a long-sought "Prester John" envoy.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His arrival was announced by King Manuel to Pope Leo X in 1513.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Although Mateus faced the distrust of Afonso's rivals, who tried to prove he was some impostor or Muslim spy, Afonso sent him to Portugal.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The king is described as having wept with joy at their report.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In February 1513, while Mateus was in Portugal, Afonso sailed to the Red Sea with a force of about 1000 Portuguese and 400 Malabaris.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He was under orders to secure that channel for Portugal.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Socotra had proved ineffective to control the Red Sea entrance and was abandoned, and Afonso's hint that Massawa could be a good Portuguese base might have been influenced by Mateus' reports.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Knowing that the Mamluks were preparing a second fleet at Suez, he wanted to advance before reinforcements arrived in Aden, and accordingly laid siege to the city.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Aden was a fortified city, but although he had scaling ladders they broke during the chaotic attack.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After half a day of fierce battle, Afonso was forced to retreat.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab, with the first European fleet to have sailed this route.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He attempted to reach Jeddah, but the winds were unfavourable and so he sheltered at Kamaran island in May, until sickness among the men and lack of fresh water forced him to retreat.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In August 1513, after a second attempt to reach Aden, he returned to India with no substantial results.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In order to destroy the power of Egypt, he wrote to King Manuel of the idea of diverting the course of the Nile river to render the whole country barren.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He also intended to steal the body of the Islamic prophet, Muhammad, and hold it for ransom until all Muslims had left the Holy Land.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Although Albuquerque's expedition failed to reach Suez, such an incursion into the Red Sea by a Christian fleet for the first time in history stunned the Muslim world, and panic spread in Cairo.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Albuquerque achieved during his term a favourable end to hostilities between the Portuguese and the Zamorin of Calicut, which had lasted since the massacre of the Portuguese in Calicut in 1502.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] As naval trade faltered and vassals defected, with no foreseeable solutions to the conflict with the Portuguese, the court of the Zamorin fell to in-fighting.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The ruling Zamorin was assassinated and replaced by a rival, under the instigation of Albuquerque, permitting peace talks to commence.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The Portuguese were allowed to build a fortress in Calicut itself, and acquired rights to obtain as much pepper and ginger as they wished, at stipulated prices, and half the customs duties of Calicut as yearly tribute.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Construction of the fortress began immediately, under the supervision of chief architect Tomás Fernandes.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] With peace concluded, in 1514 Afonso devoted himself to governing Goa and receiving embassies from Indian governors, strengthening the city and encouraging marriages of Portuguese men and local women.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At that time, Portuguese women were barred from traveling overseas in order to maintain discipline among the men on board the ships.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1511 under a policy which Afonso promulgated, the Portuguese government encouraged their explorers to marry local women.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] To promote settlement, the King of Portugal granted freeman status and exemption from Crown taxes to Portuguese men (known as *casados*, or "married men") who ventured overseas and married local women.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] With Afonso's encouragement, mixed marriages flourished, giving birth to Portuguese-Indians or *mestiços*.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He appointed local people for positions in the Portuguese administration and did not interfere with local traditions (except "sati", the practice of immolating widows, which he banned).
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In March 1514 King Manuel sent to Pope Leo X a huge and exotic embassy led by Tristão da Cunha, who toured the streets of Rome in an extravagant procession of animals from the colonies and wealth from the Indies.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His reputation reached its peak, laying foundations of the Portuguese Empire in the East.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In early 1514, Afonso sent ambassadors to Gujarat's Sultan Muzaffar Shah II, ruler of Cambay, to seek permission to build a fort on Diu, India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The mission returned without an agreement, but diplomatic gifts were exchanged, including an Indian rhinoceros.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso sent the rhino to King Manuel, making it the first living example of a rhinoceros seen in Europe since the Roman Empire.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] King Manuel named the rhino Genda after the Gujarat word for ball, and later gifted it to Pope Leo X, but before completing its journey to Italy the boat carrying the rhino sank and the animal drowned.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1515, German artist Albrecht Dürer created his famous woodcut known as Dürer's Rhinoceros, based on a description from a letter and a brief sketch made by an unknown artist who had seen the actual animal.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Dürer's interpretation of the rhino cemented the idea of how a rhino should look like in people's mindsets up until the late-eighteenth century.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1513, at Cannanore, Afonso was visited by a Persian ambassador from Shah Ismail I, who had sent ambassadors to Gujarat, Ormuz and Bijapur.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The shah's ambassador to Bijapur invited Afonso to send back an envoy to Persia.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Miguel Ferreira was sent via Ormuz to Tabriz, where he had several interviews with the shah about common goals of defeating the Mamluk sultan.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At the same time, Albuquerque decided to conclude the effective conquest of Hormuz.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He had learned that after the Portuguese retreat in 1507, a young king was reigning under the influence of a powerful Persian vizier, Reis Hamed, whom the king greatly feared.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At Ormuz in March 1515, Afonso met the king and asked the vizier to be present.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He then had him immediately stabbed and killed by his entourage, thus "freeing" the terrified king, so the island in the Persian Gulf yielded to him without resistance and remained a vassal state of the Portuguese Empire.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Ormuz itself would not be Persian territory for another century, until an English-Persian alliance finally expelled the Portuguese in 1622.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At Ormuz, Afonso met with Miguel Ferreira, returning with rich presents and an ambassador, carrying a letter from the Persian potentate Shah Ismael, inviting Afonso to become a leading lord in Persia.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] There he remained, engaging in diplomatic efforts, receiving envoys and overseeing the construction of the new fortress, while becoming increasingly ill.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] His illness was reported as early as September 1515.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In November 1515, he embarked on a journey back to Goa.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] At this time, his political enemies at the Portuguese court were planning his downfall.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] They had lost no opportunity in stirring up the jealousy of King Manuel against him, insinuating that Afonso intended to usurp power in Portuguese India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] While on his return voyage from Ormuz in the Persian Gulf, near the harbor of Chaul, he received news of a Portuguese fleet arriving from Europe, bearing dispatches announcing that he was to be replaced by his personal foe, Lopo Soares de Albergaria.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Feeling himself near death, he donned the surcoat of the Order of Santiago, of which he was a knight, and drew up his will, appointed the captain and senior officials of Ormuz, and organized a final council with his captains to decide the main matters affecting the Portuguese State of India.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He wrote a brief letter to King Manuel, asking him to confer onto his natural son "all of the high honors and rewards" that Afonso had received, and assuring Manuel of his loyalty.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] On 16 December 1515, Afonso de Albuquerque died within sight of Goa.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] As his death was known, in the city "great wailing arose", and many took to the streets to witness his body carried on a chair by his main captains, in a procession lit by torches amidst the crowd.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso's body was buried in Goa, according to his will, in the Church of Nossa Senhora da Serra (Our Lady of the Hill), which he had been built in 1513 to thank the Madonna for his escape from Kamaran island.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] That night, the population of Goa, both Hindu and Portuguese, gathered to mourn his death.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In Portugal, King Manuel's zigzagging policies continued, still trapped by the constraints of real-time medieval communication between Lisbon and India and unaware that Afonso was dead.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He organized a new Portuguese navy in Asia, with orders that Afonso (if he was still in India), be made commander-in-chief against the Sultan of Cairo's armies.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Manuel would afterwards learn that Afonso had died many months earlier, and that his reversed decision had been delivered many months too late.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] After 51 years, in 1566, his body was moved to Nossa Senhora da Graça church in Lisbon, which was ruined and rebuilt after the 1755 Great Lisbon earthquake.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] King Manuel I of Portugal was belatedly convinced of Afonso's loyalty, and endeavoured to atone for his lack of confidence in Afonso by heaping honours upon his son, Brás de Albuquerque (1500–1580), whom he renamed "Afonso" in memory of the father.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Afonso de Albuquerque was a prolific writer, having sent numerous letters during his governorship, covering topics from minor issues to major strategies.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1557 his son published his biography under the title *Commentarios do Grande Affonso d'Alboquerque*.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1572, Afonso's actions were described in *The Lusiads*, the Portuguese main epic poem by Luís Vaz de Camões (Canto X, strophes 40–49).
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] The poet praises his achievements, but has the muses frown upon the harsh rule of his men, of whom Camões was almost a contemporary fellow.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In 1934, Afonso was celebrated by Fernando Pessoa in *Mensagem*, a symbolist epic.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] In the first part of this work, called "Brasão" (Coat-of-Arms), he relates Portuguese historical protagonists to each of the fields in the Portuguese coat-of-arms, Afonso being one of the wings of the griffin headed by Henry the Navigator, the other wing being King John II.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] A variety of mango, which was created by Portuguese Jesuits in Goa via grafting techniques, was named in his honour.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Numerous homages have been paid to Afonso.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] He is featured in the Padrão dos Descobrimentos monument.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] There is a square named after him in Lisbon, which also features a bronze statue, as well as a prominent statue of his enrobed figure in a garden square in Bairro Gomes da Costa in Porto.
[src:carrack/afonso-de-albuquerque] Two Portuguese Navy ships have been named in his honour: the sloop NRP *Afonso de Albuquerque* (1884) and the warship NRP *Afonso de Albuquerque* (1934).
[src:carrack/aftcastle] The **aftercastle** (or **sterncastle**, sometimes **aftcastle**) is the stern structure behind the mizzenmast and above the transom on large sailing ships, such as carracks, caravels, galleons and galleasses.
[src:carrack/aftcastle] It usually houses the captain's cabin and perhaps additional cabins and is crowned by the poop deck, which on men-of-war provided a heightened platform from which to fire upon other ships; it was also a place of defence in the event of boarding.
[src:carrack/aftcastle] More common, but much smaller, is the forecastle.
[src:carrack/aftcastle] The corresponding term *forecastle* today is also used to describe the upper deck of a sailing ship forward of the foremast in general.
[src:carrack/aftcastle] As sailing ships evolved, the aftercastle gave way to the quarterdeck, whose span ran all the way to the main mast.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:carrack/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:carrack/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian, which is the earliest documented Semitic language, is named after the city of Akkad, a major centre of Mesopotamian civilization during the Akkadian Empire (c.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] It was written using the cuneiform script, originally used for Sumerian, but also used to write multiple languages in the region including Eblaite, Hurrian, Elamite, Old Persian and Hittite.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The influence of Sumerian on Akkadian went beyond just the cuneiform script; owing to their close proximity, a lengthy span of contact and the prestige held by the former, Sumerian significantly influenced Akkadian phonology, vocabulary and syntax.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] This mutual influence of Akkadian and Sumerian has also led scholars to describe the languages as a sprachbund.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian proper names are first attested in Sumerian texts in the mid-3rd millennium BC, and inscriptions ostensibly written in Sumerian but whose character order reveals that they were intended to be read in East Semitic (presumably early Akkadian) date back to as early as c.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] From about the 24th century BC, texts fully written in Akkadian begin to appear.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] By the 20th century BC, two variant forms of the same language were in use in Assyria and Babylonia, known as **Assyrian** and **Babylonian** respectively.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The bulk of preserved material is from this later period, corresponding to the Near Eastern Iron Age.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In total, hundreds of thousands of texts and text fragments have been excavated, covering a vast textual tradition of religious and mythological narrative, legal texts, scientific works, personal correspondence, political, civil and military events, economic tracts and many other examples.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] However, its decline began in the Iron Age, during the Neo-Assyrian Empire, by about the 8th century BC (Tiglath-Pileser III), in favour of Old Aramaic.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] By the Hellenistic period, the language was largely confined to scholars and priests working in temples in Assyria and Babylonia.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The last known Akkadian cuneiform document dates from the 1st century AD.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Mandaic and Suret are two (Northwest Semitic) Neo-Aramaic languages that retain some Akkadian vocabulary and grammatical features.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian is a fusional language with grammatical case.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Like all Semitic languages, Akkadian uses the system of consonantal roots.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Kültepe texts, which were written in Old Assyrian, include Hittite loanwords and names, which constitute the oldest record of any Indo-European language.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Left: Sumero-Akkadian cuneiform syllabary, used by early Akkadian rulers.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] ), appears vertically in the right column.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian is a Semitic language of the East Semitic branch.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Its relatives in the East Semitic branch include Eblaite.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] This group differs from the Northwest Semitic languages (such as Aramaic) and South Semitic languages (such as Geʽez) in its subject–object–verb word order, while the other Semitic languages usually have either a verb–subject–object or subject–verb–object order.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In contrast to most other Semitic languages, Akkadian has only one non-sibilant fricative: ḫ [x].
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian lost both the glottal and pharyngeal fricatives, which are characteristic of the other Semitic languages.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Until the Old Babylonian period, the Akkadian sibilants were exclusively affricated.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Additionally Akkadian is the only Semitic language to use the prepositions *ina* and *ana* (locative case, English *in*/*on*/*with*, and dative-locative case, *for*/*to*, respectively).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Other Semitic languages like Arabic, Hebrew and Aramaic have the prepositions *bi/bə* and *li/lə* (locative and dative, respectively).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The origin of the Akkadian spatial prepositions is unknown.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Semitic languages are further grouped by most linguists into the Afroasiatic macrofamily of languages, meaning that Akkadian is distantly related to Ancient Egyptian, as well as many other languages spoken historically and currently across northern and western Africa and West Asia.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Old Akkadian is preserved on clay tablets dating back to c.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] It was written using cuneiform, a script adopted from the Sumerians using wedge-shaped symbols pressed in wet clay.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] As employed by Akkadian scribes, the adapted cuneiform script could represent either (a) Sumerian logograms (*i.e.*, picture-based characters representing entire words), (b) Sumerian syllables, (c) Akkadian syllables, or (d) phonetic complements.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In Akkadian the script practically became a fully fledged syllabic script, and the original logographic nature of cuneiform became secondary, though logograms for frequent words such as 'god' and 'temple' continued to be used.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] For this reason, the sign *AN* can on the one hand be a logogram for the word *ilum* ('god') and on the other signify the god Anu or even the syllable *-an-*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Additionally, this sign was used as a determinative for divine names.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Another peculiarity of Akkadian cuneiform is that many signs do not have a well defined phonetic value.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Certain signs, such as **AḪ**, do not distinguish between the different vowel qualities.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Nor is there any coordination in the other direction; the syllable **-ša-**, for example, is rendered by the sign **ŠA**, but also by the sign **NĪĜ**.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Both of these are often used for the same syllable in the same text.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Cuneiform was in many ways unsuited to Akkadian: among its flaws was its inability to represent important phonemes in Semitic, including a glottal stop, pharyngeals, and emphatic consonants.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In addition, cuneiform was a syllabary writing system—i.e., a consonant plus vowel comprised one writing unit—frequently inappropriate for a Semitic language made up of triconsonantal roots (i.e., three consonants plus any vowels).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] One of the earliest known Akkadian inscriptions was found on a bowl at Ur, addressed to the very early pre-Sargonic king Meskiagnunna of Ur (c.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] 2485–2450 BC) by his queen Gan-saman, who is thought to have been from Akkad.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Akkadian Empire, established by Sargon of Akkad, introduced the Akkadian language (the "language of Akkad") as a written language, adapting Sumerian cuneiform orthography for the purpose.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] During the Middle Bronze Age (Old Assyrian and Old Babylonian period), the language virtually displaced Sumerian, which is assumed to have been extinct as a living language by the 18th century BC.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Old Akkadian, which was used until the end of the 3rd millennium BC, differed from both Babylonian and Assyrian, and was displaced by these dialects.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] By the 21st century BC Babylonian and Assyrian, which were to become the primary dialects, were easily distinguishable.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Old Babylonian, along with the closely related dialect Mariotic, is clearly more innovative than the Old Assyrian dialect and the more distantly related Eblaite language.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] For this reason, forms like *lu-prus* ('I will decide') were first encountered in Old Babylonian instead of the older *la-prus*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] While generally more archaic, Assyrian developed certain innovations as well, such as the "Assyrian vowel harmony".
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Eblaite was even more so, retaining a productive dual and a relative pronoun declined in case, number and gender.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Both of these had already disappeared in Old Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Over 20,000 cuneiform tablets in Old Assyrian have been recovered from the Kültepe site in Anatolia.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Most of the archaeological evidence is typical of Anatolia rather than of Assyria, but the use both of cuneiform and the dialect is the best indication of Assyrian presence.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Old Babylonian was the language of king Hammurabi and his code, which is one of the oldest collections of laws in the world.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] (see Code of Ur-Nammu.) Old Assyrian developed as well during the second millennium BC, but because it was a purely popular language—kings wrote in Babylonian—few long texts are preserved.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] It was, however, notably used in the correspondence of Assyrian traders in Anatolia in the 20th–18th centuries BC and that even led to its temporary adoption as a diplomatic language by various local Anatolian polities during that time.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Middle Babylonian period started in the 16th century BC.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The division is marked by the Kassite invasion of Babylonia around 1550 BC.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Kassites, who reigned for 300 years, gave up their own language in favor of Akkadian, but they had little influence on the language.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] At its apogee, Middle Babylonian was the written language of diplomacy of the entire Ancient Near East, including Egypt (Amarna Period).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] During this period, a large number of loan words were included in the language from Northwest Semitic languages and Hurrian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] However, the use of these words was confined to the fringes of the Akkadian-speaking territory.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] From 1500 BC onwards, the Assyrian language is termed Middle Assyrian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] It was the language of the Middle Assyrian Empire.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] However, the Babylonian cultural influence was strong and the Assyrians wrote royal inscriptions, religious and most scholarly texts in Middle Babylonian, whereas Middle Assyrian was used mostly in letters and administrative documents.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] During the first millennium BC, Akkadian progressively lost its status as a *lingua franca*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In the beginning, from around 1000 BC, Akkadian and Aramaic were of equal status, as can be seen in the number of copied texts: clay tablets were written in Akkadian, while scribes writing on papyrus and leather used Aramaic.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] From this period on, one speaks of Neo-Babylonian and Neo-Assyrian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Neo-Assyrian experienced an upswing in popularity in the 10th century BC when the Assyrian kingdom became a major power with the Neo-Assyrian Empire.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] During the existence of that empire, however, Neo-Assyrian began to turn into a chancellery language, being marginalized by Old Aramaic.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The dominance of the Neo-Assyrian Empire under Tiglath-Pileser III over Aram-Damascus in the middle of the 8th century led to the establishment of Aramaic as a *lingua franca* of the empire, rather than it being eclipsed by Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Texts written 'exclusively' in Neo-Assyrian disappear within 10 years of Nineveh's destruction in 612 BC.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Under the Achaemenids, Aramaic continued to prosper, but Assyrian continued its decline.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The language's final demise came about during the Hellenistic period when it was further marginalized by Koine Greek, even though Neo-Assyrian cuneiform remained in use in literary tradition well into Parthian times.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Neo-Assyrian was used in some surviving tablets containing poetry and also more prominently in surviving letters of royal correspondence.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Because of the multilingual nature of the empire, many loan words are attested as entering the Assyrian language during the Neo-Assyrian period.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The number of surviving documents written in cuneiform grew considerably fewer in the late reign of Ashurbanipal, which suggests that the language was declining since it is probably attributable to an increased use of Aramaic, often written on perishable materials like leather scrolls or papyrus.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Neo-Assyrian Akkadian language did not disappear completely until around the end of the 6th century BC however, well into the subsequent post-imperial period.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Similarly, the Persian conquest of the Mesopotamian kingdoms contributed to the decline of Babylonian, from that point on known as Late Babylonian, as a popular language.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] However, the language was still used in its written form.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Even after the Greek invasion under Alexander the Great in the 4th century BC, Akkadian was still a contender as a written language, but spoken Akkadian was likely extinct by this time, or at least rarely used.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The last positively identified Akkadian text comes from the 1st century AD.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The latest known text in cuneiform Babylonian is an astronomical almanac dated to 79/80 AD.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] However, the latest cuneiform texts are almost entirely written in Sumerian logograms.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Iamblichus, a 2nd century Syrian novelist, may have been one of the last known people to know Babylonian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Akkadian language began to be rediscovered when Carsten Niebuhr in 1767 was able to make extensive copies of cuneiform texts and published them in Denmark.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The deciphering of the texts started immediately, and bilinguals, in particular Old Persian-Akkadian bilinguals, were of great help.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Since the texts contained several royal names, isolated signs could be identified, and were presented in 1802 by Georg Friedrich Grotefend.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] By this time it was already evident that Akkadian was a Semitic language, and the final breakthrough in deciphering the language came from Edward Hincks, Henry Rawlinson and Jules Oppert in the middle of the 19th century.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In the early 21st century it was shown that automatic high-quality translation of Akkadian can be achieved using natural language processing methods such as convolutional neural networks.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The following table summarises the dialects of Akkadian identified with certainty so far.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Sommerfeld 2003) believe that the Old Akkadian variant used in the older texts is not an ancestor of the later Assyrian and Babylonian dialects, but rather a separate dialect that was replaced by these two dialects and which died out early.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Eblaite, formerly thought of as yet another Akkadian dialect, is now generally considered a separate East Semitic language.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Because Akkadian as a spoken language is extinct and no contemporary descriptions of the pronunciation are known, little can be said with certainty about the phonetics and phonology of Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Some conclusions can be made, however, due to the relationship to the other Semitic languages and variant spellings of Akkadian words.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The following table presents the consonants of the Akkadian language, as distinguished in Akkadian cuneiform.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The reconstructed phonetic value of a phoneme is given in IPA transcription, alongside its standard (DMG-Umschrift) transliteration in angle brackets `⟨ ⟩`.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] 3. ⟨š⟩ represented the voiceless alveolar fricative /s/ in the Assyrian dialect and a voiceless postalveolar fricative /ʃ/ in the Babylonian dialect.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Alternatively transcribed as ⟨x⟩, ⟨ġ⟩, or simply ⟨h⟩.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian ⟨r⟩ is usually interpreted as an alveolar [r], but some authors reconstruct it as a guttural [ʁ] .
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Akkadian emphatic consonants are typically reconstructed as ejectives, which are thought to be the oldest realization of emphatics across the Semitic languages.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] One piece of evidence for this is that Akkadian shows a development known as Geers's law, where one of two emphatic consonants dissimilates to the corresponding non-emphatic consonant.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] For the sibilants, traditionally ⟨š⟩ has been held to be postalveolar /ʃ/, and ⟨s⟩, ⟨z⟩, ⟨ṣ⟩ analyzed as fricatives; but attested assimilations in Akkadian suggest otherwise.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] For example, when the possessive suffix *-šu* is added to the root *awat* ('word'), it is written *awassu* ('his word') even though *šš* would be expected.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The most straightforward interpretation of this shift from *tš* to *ss*, is that ⟨s, ṣ⟩ form a pair of voiceless alveolar affricates /t͡s/ /t͡sʼ/, ⟨š⟩ is a voiceless alveolar sibilant /s/, and ⟨z⟩ is a voiced alveolar affricate or fricative /d͡z/~/z/.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The assimilation is then [awat+su] > /awatt͡su/.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In this vein, an alternative transcription of ⟨š⟩ is ⟨s̱⟩, with the macron below indicating a soft (lenis) articulation in Semitic transcription.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Other interpretations are possible. /ʃ/ could have been assimilated to the preceding /t/, yielding /ts/, which would later have been simplified to /ss/.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The rhotic ⟨r⟩ has traditionally been interpreted as a voiced alveolar trill /r/ but its pattern of alternation with ⟨ḫ⟩ suggests it was a fricative (either uvular /ʁ/ or velar /ɣ/).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] In the Hellenistic period, Akkadian ⟨r⟩ was transcribed using the Greek ρ, indicating it was pronounced similarly as an alveolar sound (though Greeks may also have perceived a uvular trill as ρ).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Several Proto-Semitic phonemes are lost in Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The Proto-Semitic glottal stop **ʔ*, as well as the fricatives **ʕ*, **h*, **ḥ* are lost as consonants, either by sound change or orthographically, but they gave rise to the vowel quality *e* not exhibited in Proto-Semitic.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The voiceless lateral fricatives (**ś, *ṣ́*) merged with the sibilants as in Canaanite, leaving 19 consonantal phonemes.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Old Akkadian preserved the /*ś/ phoneme longest but it eventually merged with /*š/, beginning in the Old Babylonian period.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The existence of a back mid-vowel /o/ has been proposed, but the cuneiform writing gives no good proof for this.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] There is limited contrast between different u-signs in lexical texts, but this scribal differentiation may reflect the superimposition of the Sumerian phonological system (for which an /o/ phoneme has also been proposed), rather than a separate phoneme in Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] All consonants and vowels appear in long and short forms.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Long consonants are transliterated as double consonants, and inconsistently written as such in cuneiform.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Long vowels are transliterated with a macron (ā, ē, ī, ū) or a circumflex (â, ê, î, û), the latter being used for long vowels arising from the contraction of vowels in hiatus.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The distinction between long and short is phonemic, and is used in the grammar; for example, *iprusu* ('that he decided') versus *iprusū* ('they decided').
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] There is broad agreement among most Assyriologists about Akkadian stress patterns.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] According to this widely accepted system, the place of stress in Akkadian is completely predictable and sensitive to syllable weight.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] There are three syllable weights: *light* (ending in -V); *heavy* (ending in -V̄ or -VC), and *superheavy* (ending in -V̂, -V̄C or -V̂C).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] If the last syllable is superheavy, it is stressed, otherwise the rightmost heavy non-final syllable is stressed.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] If a word contains only light syllables, the first syllable is stressed.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] It has also been argued that monosyllabic words generally are not stressed but rather function as clitics.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The special behaviour of /V̂/ syllables is explained by their functioning, in accordance with their historical origin, as sequences of two syllables, of which the first one bears stress.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] A rule of Akkadian phonology is that certain short (and probably unstressed) vowels are dropped.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] The rule is that the last vowel of a succession of syllables that end in a short vowel is dropped, for example the declinational root of the verbal adjective of a root PRS is *PaRiS-*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Thus the masculine singular nominative is *PaRS-um* (< **PaRiS-um*) but the feminine singular nominative is *PaRiStum* (< **PaRiS-at-um*).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p01] Additionally there is a general tendency of syncope of short vowels in the later stages of Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Most roots of the Akkadian language consist of three consonants, called the radicals, but some roots are composed of four consonants, so-called quadriradicals.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The radicals are occasionally represented in transcription in upper-case letters, for example *PRS* (to decide).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Between and around these radicals various infixes, suffixes and prefixes, having word generating or grammatical functions, are inserted.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The resulting consonant-vowel pattern differentiates the original meaning of the root.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The middle radical can be geminated, which is represented by a doubled consonant in transcription, and sometimes in the cuneiform writing itself.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The consonants *ʔ*, *w*, *j* and *n* are termed "weak radicals" and roots containing these radicals give rise to irregular forms.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Formally, Akkadian has three numbers (singular, dual and plural) and three cases (nominative, accusative and genitive).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] However, even in the earlier stages of the language, the dual number is vestigial, and its use is largely confined to natural pairs (eyes, ears, etc.).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] In the dual and plural, the accusative and genitive are merged into a single oblique case.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Akkadian, unlike Arabic, has only "sound" plurals formed by means of a plural ending.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Broken plurals are not formed by changing the word stem.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] As in all Semitic languages, some masculine nouns take the prototypically feminine plural ending (*-āt*).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The nouns *šarrum* (king) and *šarratum* (queen) and the adjective *dannum* (strong) will serve to illustrate the case system of Akkadian.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] As is clear from the above table, the adjective and noun endings differ only in the masculine plural.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Certain nouns, primarily those referring to geography, can also form a locative ending in *-um* in the singular and the resulting forms serve as adverbials.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] These forms are generally not productive, but in the Neo-Babylonian the *um*-locative replaces several constructions with the preposition *ina*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] In the later stages of Akkadian, the mimation (word-final *-m*) and nunation (dual final *-n*) that occurred at the end of most case endings disappeared, except in the locative.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Later, the nominative and accusative singular of masculine nouns collapsed to *-u* and in Neo-Babylonian most word-final short vowels were dropped.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] As a result, case differentiation disappeared from all forms except masculine plural nouns.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] However, many texts continued the practice of writing the case endings, although often sporadically and incorrectly.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] As the most important contact language throughout this period was Aramaic, which itself lacks case distinctions, it is possible that Akkadian's loss of cases was an areal as well as phonological phenomenon.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] As is also the case in other Semitic languages, Akkadian nouns may appear in a variety of "states" depending on their grammatical function in a sentence.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The basic form of the noun is the *status rectus* (the governed state), which is the form as described above, complete with case endings.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] In addition to this, Akkadian has the *status absolutus* (the absolute state) and the *status constructus* (construct state).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The latter is found in all other Semitic languages, while the former appears only in Akkadian and some dialects of Aramaic.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The *status absolutus* is characterised by the loss of a noun's case ending (e.g.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] It is relatively uncommon, and is used chiefly to mark the predicate of a nominal sentence, in fixed adverbial expressions, and in expressions relating to measurements of length, weight, and the like.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The *status constructus* is more common by far, and has a much wider range of applications.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] It is employed when a noun is followed by another noun in the genitive, a pronominal suffix, or a verbal clause in the subjunctive, and typically takes the *shortest form of the noun which is phonetically possible*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] There are numerous exceptions to this general rule, usually involving potential violations of the language's phonological limitations.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Most obviously, Akkadian does not tolerate word-final consonant clusters, so nouns like *kalbum* (dog) and *maḫrum* (front) would have illegal construct state forms **kalb* and **maḫr* unless modified.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] In many of these instances, the first vowel of the word is simply repeated (e.g.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] This rule, however, does not always hold true, especially in nouns where a short vowel has historically been elided (e.g.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] In these cases, the lost vowel is restored in the construct state (so *šaknum* yields *šakin*).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] A genitive relation can also be expressed with the relative preposition *ša*, and the noun that the genitive phrase depends on appears in status rectus.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The alliances of the Ruler of Ešnunna (lit.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The same preposition is also used to introduce true relative clauses, in which case the verb is placed in the subjunctive mood.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The Akkadian verb has six finite verb aspects (preterite, perfect, present, imperative, precative, and vetitive (the negative form of precative)) and three infinite forms (infinitive, participle and verbal adjective).
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The preterite is used for actions that are seen by the speaker as having occurred at a single point in time.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The present is primarily imperfective in meaning and is used for concurrent and future actions as well as past actions with a temporal dimension.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The final three finite forms are injunctive where the imperative and the precative together form a paradigm for positive commands and wishes, and the vetitive is used for negative wishes.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The periphrastic prohibitive, formed by the present form of the verb and the negative adverb lā, is used to express negative commands.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The infinitive of the Akkadian verb is a verbal noun, and in contrast to some other languages the Akkadian infinitive can be declined in case.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The verbal adjective is an adjectival form and designates the state or the result of the action of the verb, and consequently the exact meaning of the verbal adjective is determined by the semantics of the verb itself.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The participle, which can be active or passive, is another verbal adjective and its meaning is similar to the English gerund.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The table below shows the different affixes attached to the preterite aspect of the verb root PRS "to decide"; and as can be seen, the grammatical genders differ only in the second person singular and third person plural.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Subjunctive, used in dependent clauses, is marked in forms which do not end in a vowel by the suffix *-u* (compare Arabic and Ugaritic subjunctives) but is otherwise unmarked.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] In the later stages of most dialects, the subjunctive is indistinct, as short final vowels were mostly lost.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Venitive or allative, not a mood in the strictest sense, being a development of the first-person dative pronominal suffix *-am*/*-m*/*-nim*.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] With verbs of motion, it often indicates motion toward an object or person (*e.g.*, *illik*, "he went" vs.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] However, this pattern is not consistent, even in earlier stages of the language, and its use often appears to serve a stylistic rather than morphological or lexical function.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Akkadian verbs have thirteen separate derived stems formed on each root.
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] The basic, underived, stem is the G-stem (from the German Grundstamm, meaning "basic stem").
[src:carrack/akkadian-language-p02] Causative or intensive forms are formed with the doubled D-stem, and it gets its name from the doubled-middle radical that is characteristic of this form.
